doc.author: The Who
description:
The Who (1964-1982) is an English rock band famous for songs like Pinball Wizard, My Generation and Behind Blue Eyes; however less known songs like I Don't Even Know Myself really speak to what the band was about. They were able to capture the change in culture between the 50's morals to 60's lack thereof; a time that left a whole generation unsure about where they fit in to the grander scheme of things. Their sound was also highly transitional. The band combined Rhythm and Blues with Rock, Pop and Punk into a sound that was unique to them.

They sold over 100 million records, released 27 hit singles and had 18 Gold Albums. The band was a major influence for artists like Led Zepplin and The Clash. In 1990, they were inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame. Many consider them to be one of the best and most influential bands of all time.

doc.author: Dylan, Bob
description:
Bob Dylan is an American singer-songwriter who rose to prominence in the 1960s thanks to his folk songs (many of which have themes of social protest).  He later reacted against the acoustic folk movement by "plugging in", employing electric guitar and a full band in his recordings.  His influence on many key artists in rock music (examples include John Lennon, Patti Smith, and Bruce Springsteen) has earned him special awards from U.S. President Barack Obama and the Pulitzer Prize Committee, among others.

All of the songs included in this collection were written by Dylan.  Four of these recordings ("Blowin' in the Wind", "Masters of War", and "With God On Our Side") are performed by Dylan himself.  "A Hard Rain's A-Gonna Fall" is performed by Texas-based folk duo Carrie Elkin and Danny Schmidt, while "The Times They Are A-Changin'" is performed by contemporary roots-rock band Of A Revolution (better known as O.A.R.).

This collection includes a classroom activity related to the song "Blowin' in the Wind."

Synopsis: Franklin's family lives in, well, a pigsty. As a meticulously neat piglet, Franklin finds his family's slovenly ways a great embarrassment, and he dares not encourage visitors. His father chooses the perfect spot to hang the picture, but Franklin asks him if he could first wash the wall.
